We know that the minimum of the function is 0 and the maximum is 120,
which means that we are looking for a trigonometric function of the form

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle 60 + 60\sin(f(t))
\end{align*} or

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle 60 + 60\cos(f(t))
\end{align*}

for some function $\displaystyle f(t)$.

Then we use the fact that the period is 11 and that the maximum occurs
for $t=2000$:

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  The period of $\sin(t)$ and $\cos(t)$ is $2\pi$. What factor is the
  argument multiplied by to get a period of 1? A period of 11?
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  $\sin(t)$ has a maximum at $t=\pi/2$ while $\cos(t)$ has a maximum at
  $t=0$. How can you shift the function left or right to shift the
  maximum to $t=2000$?
\end{itemize}

