Substituting $t = 2000$ into the given possibilities gives

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
(a)
$N = 60 + 120\sin\left(\frac{2\pi}{11}(t - 2000 ) + \frac{\pi}{2}\right) = 60 + 120\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right) = {\color{red} 180}$\end{description}

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
(b)
$N = 60 + 60\sin\left(\frac{11}{2\pi}(t + 2000 ) \right) = {\color{red} 60 + 60\sin\left(\frac{22000}{\pi}\right)}$\end{description}

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
(c)
$N = 60 + 60\cos\left(\frac{11}{2\pi}(t + 2000) \right) = {\color{red} 60 + 60\cos\left(\frac{22000}{\pi}\right)}$\end{description}

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
(d)
$N = 60 + 60\sin\left(\frac{2\pi}{11}(t - 2000) \right) = 60 + 60\sin(0) = {\color{red} 60}$\end{description}

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
(e)
$N = 60 + 60\cos\left(\frac{2\pi}{11}(t - 2000 ) \right) = 60 + 60\cos(0) = {\color{OliveGreen} 120}$\end{description}

Therefore, the answer is ${\color{blue}\text{(E)}}$.

A more methodical method of approaching the problem is as follows:

We know that the minimum of the function is 0 and the maximum is 120,
which means that we are looking for a trigonometric function of the form

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle 60 + 60\sin(f(t))
\end{align*} or

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle 60 + 60\cos(f(t))
\end{align*}

for some function $\displaystyle f(t)$.

Since the period is 11 years, we see that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle f(t) = \frac{2\pi}{11} \cdot g(t)
\end{align*}

for some other function $\displaystyle g(t)$.

Lastly, we notice that a peak was detected in 2000. If we used the
cosine function, we would have

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle g(t) = t-2000
\end{align*}

since the peak of the cosine function is at 0 (up to integer multiples
of $2 \pi$). If we used the sine function, we would have

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle f(t) = \frac{2\pi}{11} \cdot g(t) + \frac{\pi}{2}
\end{align*} and

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle g(t) = t-2000
\end{align*}

since the peak of the sine function occurs at $\tfrac{\pi}{2}$ up to
integer multiples of $2 \pi$.

Thus, the possible answers are:

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle  N = 60 + 60\sin\left(\frac{2\pi}{11} (t-2000) + \frac{\pi}{2}\right)
\end{align*}
or

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle  N = 60 + 60\cos\left(\frac{2\pi}{11}(t-2000)\right)
\end{align*}

The latter is a possible choice in the question, and so the answer is
${\color{blue}\text{(E)}}$.
